<body>

<h1>Prime' New Generation — System Design</h1>

<p class="lead"><b>What this is:</b> Prime' New Generation is a web app that helps students plan studying abroad.
It lets them take a readiness <b>assessment</b>, compare <b>countries</b>, read a community <b>forum</b>,
and <b>contact</b> advisors — in <b>5 languages</b> (English, Arabic, French, Spanish, Hindi) with
light/dark themes. This document explains the system <b>as it is today</b> (a static front-end), then
lays out a <b>phased roadmap</b> to grow it into a full production product.</p>

<h2>1. The big picture (1-minute version)</h2>
<p>Today Prime' New Generation is a <b>100% client-side static website</b>. There is <b>no backend, no database,
no server code</b>. Everything runs in the visitor's browser. Data (countries, forum threads,
translations) is hard-coded in JavaScript files. The assessment result is delivered by opening a
<b>WhatsApp link</b>, and the contact form opens the user's email client (<code>mailto</code>).</p>

<pre>            +---------------------------------------------+
            |                 BROWSER                     |
            |                                             |
   User --> |  HTML pages  ->  JS modules  ->  rendered UI|
            |   (index,        (i18n,                     |
            |    countries,     components,               |
            |    assessment,    countries,               |
            |    forum,         assessment,               |
            |    contact)       forum, contact)           |
            |                                             |
            |  localStorage: theme + language preference  |
            +---------------+-----------------------------+
                            |  (only outbound action today)
                            v
                  WhatsApp link  /  mailto email</pre>

<p><b>Why this design?</b> It is cheap, fast, and needs zero servers — perfect for a launch/MVP. The
trade-off: no accounts, no saved data, no real forum, and content edits require a developer. The
roadmap (Section 6) addresses each of those.</p>

<h2>2. Current architecture</h2>

<h3>2.1 Technology stack</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Layer</th><th>Technology</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
<tr><td>Markup</td><td>Plain HTML5, one file per page</td><td>No framework</td></tr>
<tr><td>Styling</td><td>Hand-written CSS (styles.css, rtl.css)</td><td>CSS variables for theming; RTL file for Arabic</td></tr>
<tr><td>Logic</td><td>Vanilla JavaScript (IIFE modules on window.*)</td><td>No build step, no bundler</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fonts</td><td>Google Fonts (Plus Jakarta Sans)</td><td>Loaded via CDN</td></tr>
<tr><td>State</td><td>localStorage</td><td>Stores theme + chosen language only</td></tr>
<tr><td>Hosting</td><td>Static file host (any)</td><td>GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, S3</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>2.2 File / folder map</h3>
<pre>younus/
+-- index.html             # Home / landing page
+-- countries.html         # Grid of all destinations
+-- country-details.html   # Single-country detail view
+-- assessment.html        # 13-step readiness wizard
+-- forum.html             # Community threads (mock, display-only)
+-- contact.html           # Contact form (mailto)
+-- travel video.mp4       # Hero background video
|
+-- css/
|   +-- styles.css         # All component + layout styles, theme variables
|   +-- rtl.css            # Right-to-left overrides for Arabic
|
+-- i18n/                  # Translation dictionaries (one file per language)
|   +-- en.js  ar.js  fr.js  es.js  hi.js
|
+-- js/
    +-- i18n.js            # Translation ENGINE (reads dictionaries, swaps text)
    +-- components.js      # Shared navbar + footer + theme + menu (every page)
    +-- countries.js       # Country DATA + rendering
    +-- assessment.js      # 13-step wizard + scoring + WhatsApp result
    +-- forum.js           # Mock threads + category filter
    +-- contact.js         # Contact form handling (mailto)</pre>

<h3>2.3 How the pieces talk to each other</h3>
<p>The app uses a <b>simple global-object pattern</b> instead of imports. Each JS file wraps itself in
an IIFE and exposes one object on <code>window</code> — e.g. <code>window.I18N</code>,
<code>window.Countries</code>, <code>window.SITE</code>. Pages load scripts in a fixed order so
dependencies exist before they are used: dictionaries &rarr; engine &rarr; shared UI &rarr; page logic.</p>
<p>Coordination happens through <b>custom DOM events</b>:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>components:ready</code> — fired after navbar/footer are injected. Pages wait for this before rendering their own content.</li>
<li><code>languagechange</code> — fired when the user switches language. Every module that shows text re-renders.</li>
</ul>

<h2>3. How each part works, step by step</h2>

<h3>3.1 Internationalization (i18n) — the heart of the app</h3>
<p><b>Goal:</b> the same page shows in 5 languages and flips to right-to-left for Arabic, without reloading.</p>
<ol>
<li><b>Dictionaries</b> live in <code>i18n/*.js</code> — nested objects of keys &rarr; translated strings (e.g. <code>home.hero.title</code>). One file per language.</li>
<li>On load, <b>js/i18n.js (the engine)</b> reads the saved language from localStorage (default English) or guesses from the browser.</li>
<li>The engine scans the DOM for every element with a <b>data-i18n="some.key"</b> attribute and fills its text from the active dictionary.</li>
<li>It sets <code>&lt;html lang&gt;</code> and <code>dir="ltr|rtl"</code>. For Arabic, <code>dir="rtl"</code> activates rtl.css.</li>
<li>When the user picks a new language, the engine updates localStorage, re-translates the DOM, and <b>fires languagechange</b> so data-driven sections re-render.</li>
</ol>
<p><b>Localized data fields</b> use a per-language map, e.g. <code>{ en: "Southern Europe", ar: "...", fr: ... }</code>. A helper <code>L(field)</code> picks the current language and falls back to English.</p>

<h3>3.2 Shared components (navbar, footer, theme) — components.js</h3>
<ul>
<li>Injects the navbar/footer into placeholder divs on every page (no copy-paste).</li>
<li>Holds <b>site config</b> in one place — brand, WhatsApp number, email, social links. <b>This is the single spot to edit contact details.</b></li>
<li>Wires the <b>light/dark theme</b> toggle, persisted under <code>Prime' New Generation_theme</code>. A tiny inline head script applies the saved theme before paint to avoid a flash.</li>
<li>Builds the mobile menu and scroll-reveal animations; fires <b>components:ready</b> when done.</li>
</ul>

<h3>3.3 Countries — countries.js</h3>
<p>A hard-coded <code>DATA</code> array; each entry has id, flag, tuition/living costs, proof-of-funds
amount, intakes, work rules, universities, and localized desc/notes. Three render functions:
home strip (3 cards), the full grid, and the detail view (reads <code>?id=spain</code> from the URL).
Re-renders on language change.</p>

<h3>3.4 Assessment — assessment.js (most complex feature)</h3>
<p>A <b>13-step wizard</b> producing a "readiness score" sent to an advisor over WhatsApp.</p>
<ol>
<li><code>STEPS</code> describes each question. Types: basic (name/age/phone), year, and options (multiple choice).</li>
<li>Each option carries a <b>score s (0 to 1)</b>; each question carries a <b>weight w</b> (e.g. "Can you prove the funds?" has w=3, the most important; cosmetic questions have w=0.5).</li>
<li>Answers are kept <b>in memory</b> only — a refresh loses progress.</li>
<li>The wizard renders one step at a time with a progress bar; Back/Next navigate.</li>
<li>It computes a <b>weighted average</b>: score = &Sigma;(s &times; w) / &Sigma;(w), scaled to a percentage, shown in a circular ring.</li>
<li>The result + answers are formatted into a message opened as a <b>WhatsApp link</b> for follow-up.</li>
</ol>

<h3>3.5 Forum — forum.js</h3>
<p>A <b>display-only mock</b>: hard-coded threads with author, category, reply/view counts, localized
title/excerpt, and a category filter. No posting, persistence, or real users yet — a visual preview of a future feature.</p>

<h3>3.6 Contact — contact.js</h3>
<p>A form that validates input and opens the user's email client via <code>mailto</code> (no server receives it).</p>

<h2>4. Data model</h2>
<p>Today "data" = JavaScript objects in source files. As a backend is added (Phase 2+), these become
database tables. <code>{lang}</code> marks a field stored per-language.</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Country</th><th>Assessment (submission)</th><th>ForumThread</th><th>User (Phase 2)</th></tr>
<tr>
<td>id (PK)<br>flag, name<br>region {lang}<br>tuition, living, proof<br>langs<br>intake {lang}<br>work {lang}<br>unis []<br>desc {lang}<br>notes {lang}</td>
<td>id (PK)<br>fullName, age, phone<br>answers (JSON q2..q13)<br>score (0-100)<br>createdAt</td>
<td>id (PK)<br>author / userId (FK)<br>category<br>title {lang}<br>excerpt {lang}<br>replies, views<br>createdAt<br>&lt; ForumReply (id, body, userId, createdAt)</td>
<td>id (PK)<br>email, name<br>locale, role<br>createdAt</td>
</tr>
</table>

<h2>5. Key user flows</h2>
<h3>A) Loading any page</h3>
<pre>page.html requested
 -> head inline script applies saved theme (no flash)
 -> dictionaries load -> i18n.js translates all [data-i18n] elements
 -> countries.js loads data
 -> components.js injects navbar+footer -> fires "components:ready"
 -> page script renders its dynamic content (e.g. 3 country cards)</pre>
<h3>B) Switching language</h3>
<pre>User clicks language in navbar
 -> i18n.js saves choice to localStorage
 -> re-translates every [data-i18n] element
 -> sets &lt;html dir&gt; (rtl for Arabic -> rtl.css applies)
 -> fires "languagechange" -> countries/forum/assessment re-render</pre>
<h3>C) Taking the assessment</h3>
<pre>Start -> Q1 (basic info) -> Q2..Q13 (scored options)
 -> each answer stored in memory
 -> on finish: score = sum(s*w)/sum(w) * 100  -> shown in ring
 -> "Send to advisor" -> opens WhatsApp with score + answers</pre>

<h2>6. Phased roadmap</h2>
<p>The recommended path from today's static MVP to a robust product. Each phase is <b>shippable on its
own</b> and adds one layer of capability. Each phase assumes the previous one.</p>

<h3>Phase 0 — Hardening the current static site (days)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>SEO &amp; sharing:</b> per-page titles/meta, Open Graph tags, sitemap.xml, robots.txt, favicons.</li>
<li><b>Performance:</b> compress the large autoplay hero video, lazy-load offscreen images, preconnect/self-host fonts.</li>
<li><b>Accessibility:</b> alt text, focus states, contrast check, full keyboard navigation of the wizard.</li>
<li><b>Analytics &amp; consent:</b> privacy-friendly analytics (e.g. Plausible) + a cookie/consent notice.</li>
<li><b>Quality gates:</b> Prettier + ESLint + a GitHub Action that lints on every push.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Exit criteria:</b> Lighthouse &ge; 90 across the board; site indexed; one-click deploys.</p>

<h3>Phase 1 — Build tooling &amp; content structure (1–2 weeks)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Introduce a build step / framework:</b> Vite + vanilla JS (lighter) or Astro / SvelteKit (fuller, still static-friendly).</li>
<li><b>Externalize content</b> to JSON/Markdown so non-developers can edit it, ideally via a Git-based CMS (Decap/Netlify CMS or Sanity).</li>
<li><b>Componentize</b> navbar/footer/cards as real components instead of string injection.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Exit criteria:</b> editors change a country's tuition without touching code; one command builds and deploys.</p>

<h3>Phase 2 — Backend, accounts &amp; persistence (3–5 weeks)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Pick a backend:</b> a BaaS (Supabase/Firebase) for speed, or Node/Express / Next.js API routes on PostgreSQL for control.</li>
<li><b>Authentication:</b> email magic-link / Google sign-in; store the User table.</li>
<li><b>Persist assessments</b> server-side instead of only firing a WhatsApp link; users revisit scores, advisors get a dashboard.</li>
<li><b>Contact &rarr; real inbox:</b> a server endpoint that stores the message and emails the team (Resend/SendGrid), with rate limiting + captcha.</li>
<li><b>Security baseline:</b> input validation, HTTPS only, secrets in env vars, least-privilege DB, row-level security.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Exit criteria:</b> a user creates an account, takes the assessment, sees it saved next visit; the team reliably receives contact submissions.</p>

<h3>Phase 3 — Real community forum (3–4 weeks)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>CRUD threads &amp; replies</b> backed by the DB.</li>
<li><b>Moderation:</b> report button, admin queue, banned-word filter, rate limiting.</li>
<li><b>Engagement:</b> likes, sorting (new/top), search, email notifications on replies.</li>
<li><b>Trust &amp; safety:</b> spam detection, profanity filtering, GDPR-compliant handling.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Exit criteria:</b> authenticated users post, reply, search; moderators act on reports.</p>

<h3>Phase 4 — Advisor workflow &amp; CRM (parallel, 2–4 weeks)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>Advisor dashboard:</b> submissions sorted by score/recency with status (new &rarr; contacted &rarr; enrolled).</li>
<li><b>Lead routing &amp; WhatsApp Business API</b> for templated, trackable replies.</li>
<li><b>Document checklist per country</b> so students track their application (passport, proof of funds, acceptance letter).</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Exit criteria:</b> every assessment becomes a trackable lead worked end-to-end.</p>

<h3>Phase 5 — Scale, observability, automation (ongoing)</h3>
<ul>
<li><b>CI/CD:</b> unit tests for scoring, end-to-end with Playwright, preview deploys per PR.</li>
<li><b>Observability:</b> error tracking (Sentry), uptime monitoring, structured logs, dashboards.</li>
<li><b>Caching/CDN</b> for static assets and country pages; cache API responses.</li>
<li><b>i18n at scale:</b> a translation platform (Locize/Crowdin) + automated missing-key checks.</li>
<li><b>Data &amp; ML (optional):</b> use accumulated assessments to refine scoring weights and recommend best-fit countries.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Exit criteria:</b> confident frequent releases; problems caught before users report them.</p>

<h3>Roadmap at a glance</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Phase</th><th>Theme</th><th>Adds</th><th>Still static?</th></tr>
<tr><td>0</td><td>Hardening</td><td>SEO, perf, a11y, analytics</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>1</td><td>Tooling &amp; content</td><td>Build step, CMS, components</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td>2</td><td>Backend &amp; accounts</td><td>DB, auth, saved assessments, real contact</td><td>No (server added)</td></tr>
<tr><td>3</td><td>Forum</td><td>Real threads, moderation</td><td>No</td></tr>
<tr><td>4</td><td>Advisor/CRM</td><td>Dashboard, lead tracking, WhatsApp API</td><td>No</td></tr>
<tr><td>5</td><td>Scale</td><td>CI/CD, monitoring, CDN, ML</td><td>No</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>7. Non-functional requirements</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Area</th><th>Target</th></tr>
<tr><td>Performance</td><td>First load &lt; 2.5s on 4G; Lighthouse &ge; 90. Biggest current risk: the hero video size.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Accessibility</td><td>WCAG 2.1 AA; full keyboard support; RTL parity for Arabic.</td></tr>
<tr><td>i18n</td><td>5 languages stay in sync; no missing keys; numbers/dates localized.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Security</td><td>(Phase 2+) HTTPS only, validated inputs, secrets in env, rate limiting, GDPR consent.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Privacy</td><td>Assessment collects name/age/phone — needs a privacy policy and consent before storing.</td></tr>
<tr><td>SEO</td><td>Indexable pages, sitemap, structured data for country pages.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Reliability</td><td>(Phase 5) 99.9% uptime target; error budget tracked.</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>8. Risks &amp; decisions</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>No persistence today.</b> Assessment progress/results vanish on refresh. Accepted for MVP; fixed in Phase 2.</li>
<li><b>Hard-coded content.</b> Every country/translation edit needs a developer. Fixed in Phase 1 (CMS).</li>
<li><b>WhatsApp link as the "backend."</b> Works for a small team but isn't trackable or reliable at scale. Upgraded to WhatsApp Business API in Phase 4.</li>
<li><b>Sensitive data over mailto/WhatsApp.</b> Collecting phone numbers without a stored consent record is a privacy risk. Add a consent checkbox now and a secured store in Phase 2.</li>
<li><b>Script-order fragility.</b> The global-window + ordered-script approach breaks if files are reordered. Removed by the build step in Phase 1.</li>
<li><b>Large autoplay video.</b> Hurts mobile load and data usage. Compress / add a poster image in Phase 0.</li>
</ul>

<p style="margin-top:24px;color:#666;font-size:9pt"><i>Document owner: Prime' New Generation team. Keep this updated as phases ship — move completed items into a "Done" note and adjust the roadmap table.</i></p>

</body>
</html>
